1. What is the difference between HTTP and WebSocket communication? Draw the flow of each in text/arrows.

HTTP (HyperText Transfer Protocol) is a request-response protocol. The client sends a request to the server, the server processes it, sends a response, and then the connection closes. If the client needs new data, it must send another request.

HTTP Flow:

Client
   │
   │ HTTP Request
   ▼
Server
   │
   │ Process Request
   ▼
HTTP Response
   │
   ▼
Client

(New request is needed for more data)

Characteristics:
• Request-response communication
• Stateless protocol
• Connection closes after every request
• Used for REST APIs

In my project, HTTP is used for:
• Login
• Register
• Get Products
• Place Orders
• Load Notifications
WebSocket Communication
WebSocket creates a persistent connection between the client and server.
Once connected, both the client and server can send data to each other at any time without opening a new connection.
WebSocket Flow:
Client
   │
   │ WebSocket Handshake
   ▼
Server
   │
   │ Connection Established
   ▼
═══════════════════════════════════════
Client  ◄──────────────►  Server
      Real-Time Communication
═══════════════════════════════════════

Server ─────► Client (New Notification)
Client ─────► Server (Socket Events)

Characteristics:
• Persistent connection
• Two-way communication
• Low latency
• Best for real-time updates

In my project, WebSocket is used to send new order notifications instantly to admin users without refreshing the page.

============================================================
2. What is a Socket.IO room and why did you use one for admin users instead of broadcasting to everyone?

A Socket.IO room is a logical group of connected clients. Only the users who join that room receive the events sent to it.

In my project, when an admin logs in, the server adds the admin's socket to the "admins" room.

When a customer places an order, the server sends the notification only to the "admins" room.

Flow:

Customer Places Order
          │
          ▼
Flask Server
          │
          ▼
Create Notification
          │
          ▼
socketio.emit(..., room="admins")
          │
          ▼
Admins Room
   │              │
Admin 1       Admin 2

I used a room instead of broadcasting because broadcasting would send the notification to every connected user, including customers. That would expose admin-only information and create unnecessary network traffic.

Using a room provides:
• Only admins receive notifications.
• Better security.
• Less network traffic.
• Better scalability.

3. When a user refreshes the page, the socket disconnects and reconnects. How do previously saved notifications still appear in the bell dropdown?

When the page is refreshed, the current Socket.IO connection is disconnected.

Refresh Page
      │
      ▼
Socket Disconnects
      │
      ▼
React Reloads
      │
      ▼
Socket Reconnects

If notifications were stored only in memory, they would disappear after the refresh.

To avoid this, every notification is saved in the MySQL notifications table before being sent through Socket.IO.

After React loads again, it sends an HTTP request to fetch all saved notifications.

Flow:

React App Starts
        │
        ▼
GET /api/notifications
        │
        ▼
Flask Server
        │
        ▼
MySQL Notifications Table
        │
        ▼
Notification List
        │
        ▼
Bell Dropdown

After loading previous notifications from the database, Socket.IO is used only for receiving new notifications in real time.

Therefore:
• Database stores all notifications permanently.
• HTTP loads old notifications after refresh.
• Socket.IO delivers new notifications instantly.
4. What does socketio.emit() do versus emit() inside a @socketio.on() handler? What is the difference?
Both functions send Socket.IO events, but they are used in different situations.
socketio.emit()
socketio.emit() can be called from anywhere in the Flask application, such as HTTP routes, background tasks, or scheduled jobs.
Example:
After a customer places an order, the order API saves the notification and uses socketio.emit() to send it to the "admins" room.
This is how my project sends real-time order notifications

emit()

emit() is used only inside a Socket.IO event handler decorated with @socketio.on().

Example:

When a client sends a "join" event, the server handles it and replies using emit() to confirm the connection or room joining.
Difference:
socketio.emit()
• Can be called anywhere in the Flask application.
• Used in HTTP routes, background tasks, or scheduled jobs.
• Can send messages to all clients or a specific room.
emit()
• Can only be used inside a @socketio.on() event handler.
• Used while handling Socket.IO events.
• Commonly used to reply to the connected client.

In my project:
• socketio.emit() is used in the order API to send new order notifications to the admin room.
• emit() is used inside Socket.IO event handlers such as the join event to communicate with connected clients.
